diff:1620486543:1619236565:=56,68d55%0a%3c #foxbegin 210508-150904-394460#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Examples of a-prefixing in music %0a%3c -> - dhrutik%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c The most popular example I can think of is the song "The Times They Are A-Changing" by Bob Dylan (Linked here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=90WD_ats6eE)%0a%3c %0a%3c As such, since a-prefixing is generally a feature of languages in the Southeastern region of America, I thought country music would be the only genre to use a-prefixing. However, it turns out a-prefixing is a great way to meet the metric of a verse by adding in an extra syllable when needed. We can see examples of this in the children's song "I Saw A Ship A-Sailing" (Linked here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JVwhUpznyA0)%0a%3c %0a%3c Source for more videos and further discussion: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YTdF0TrmvY8%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210508-150904-394460#%0a
